"Vale P., Veloso V., Amorim A.","Toxin composition of a Prorocentrum lima strain isolated from the Portuguese coast",2009,"Toxicon","54","2",,"145","152",,,10.1016/j.toxicon.2009.03.026,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-67349099070&partnerID=40&md5=025424106dbc743f4be6b8fc98f58448","Instituto Nacional dos Recursos Biológicos - IPIMAR (INRB-IPIMAR), Av. Brasília, s/n, 1449-006 Lisboa, Portugal; Instituto de Oceanografia (IO), Faculdade de Ciências, Universidade de Lisboa, Campo Grande, 1749-016 Lisboa, Portugal","Vale, P., Instituto Nacional dos Recursos Biológicos - IPIMAR (INRB-IPIMAR), Av. Brasília, s/n, 1449-006 Lisboa, Portugal; Veloso, V., Instituto de Oceanografia (IO), Faculdade de Ciências, Universidade de Lisboa, Campo Grande, 1749-016 Lisboa, Portugal; Amorim, A., Instituto de Oceanografia (IO), Faculdade de Ciências, Universidade de Lisboa, Campo Grande, 1749-016 Lisboa, Portugal","Microalgae of the genus Dinophysis and Prorocentrum are known producers of okadaites, responsible for the human syndrome known as diarrhetic shellfish poisoning (DSP). In temperate regions, only species from the genus Dinophysis are commonly held responsible for shellfish contamination. This is probably related to the different ecological strategies of the two genera, namely the planktonic nature of Dinophysis versus the benthic/epiphytic nature of toxic Prorocentrum species. In recent years, the threat of global warming has drawn attention to the study of benthic toxic microalgae in southern European waters. Here we present results on the toxin production and toxin profile of a Prorocentrum lima strain isolated from the Portuguese coast. This strain, IO66-01, presented a mean growth rate of 0.49 divisions d-1, not common in temperate strains, and only comparable with tropical strains. The parent toxins found were okadaic acid (OA) and dinophysistoxin-1 (DTX1). The major diol esters were D8- and D9- congeners of both OA and DTX1. © 2009 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.","Dinophysistoxin-1; Diol esters; Okadaic acid; Portugal; Prorocentrum lima; Southern Europe; Temperate strain","dinophysistoxin 1; ester derivative; okadaic acid; article; microalga; nonhuman; Portugal; priority journal; Prorocentrum lima; toxin analysis; toxin synthesis; Animals; Chromatography, High Pressure Liquid; Dinoflagellida; Indicators and Reagents; Marine Toxins; Mass Spectrometry; Okadaic Acid; Portugal; Pyrans; Spectrometry, Mass, Electrospray Ionization; Dinophysis; Prorocentrum; Prorocentrum lima",,"dinophysistoxin 1, 81720-10-7; okadaic acid, 78111-17-8; Indicators and Reagents; Marine Toxins; Okadaic Acid, 78111-17-8; Pyrans; dinophysistoxin 1, 81720-10-7",,,,"Bouaïcha, N., Chézeau, A., Turquet, J., Quod, J.P., Puiseux-Dao, S., Morphological and toxicological variability of Prorocentrum lima clones isolated from four locations in the south-west Indian Ocean (2001) Toxicon, 39, pp. 1195-1202; Bravo, I., Fernández, M.L., Ramilo, I., Martínez, A., Toxin composition of the toxic dinoflagellate Prorocentrum lima isolated from different locations along the Galician coast (NW Spain) (2001) Toxicon, 39, pp. 1537-1545; Cruz, P.G., Daranas, A.H., Fernández, J.J., Souto, M.L., Norte, M., DTX5c, a new OA sulphate ester derivative from cultures of Prorocentrum belizeanum (2006) Toxicon, 47, pp. 920-924; Dodge, J.D., The prorocentrales (Dinophyceae). II. Revision of the taxonomy within the genus Prorocentrum (1975) Bot. J. Linn. Soc., 71, pp. 103-125; FAO, (2004) Marine Biotoxins, FAO Food and Nutrition Paper, 80. , Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations, Rome 278pp; Faust, M.A., Morphology of ciguatera-causing Prorocentrum lima (Pyrrophyta) from widely differing sites (1991) J. Phycol., 27, pp. 642-648; Faust, M.A., Alternate sexual reproduction of Prorocentrum lima in culture (1993) Toxic Phytoplankton Blooms in the Sea, pp. 115-120. , Smayda T.J., and Shimizu Y. (Eds), Elsevier, New York; Faust, M.A., Larsen, J., Moestrup, Ø., (199